00:09:08.005 --> 00:09:10.132  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
then it shifted to something more legal.

124
00:09:10.216 --> 00:09:12.301  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Segregation. Jim Crow.

125
00:09:13.928 --> 00:09:18.099  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Alexander] <i>Laws were passed</i>
<i>that relegated African Americans</i>

126
00:09:18.182 --> 00:09:21.060  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
to a permanent second-class status.

127
00:09:25.439 --> 00:09:30.277  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
These things really begin to live out
the prophecy that Griffith was making

128
00:09:30.361 --> 00:09:32.238  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
about the way that race operates.

129
00:09:32.321 --> 00:09:35.282  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
And this fear of crime
is central to all of this.

130
00:09:35.366 --> 00:09:37.577  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Every time you saw a sign
that said "white and colored,"

131
00:09:37.660 --> 00:09:39.912  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
every time you had to deal
with the indignation

132
00:09:40.496 --> 00:09:42.498  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
of being told you can't go
through the front door.

133
00:09:42.582 --> 00:09:44.333  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Every day you weren't allowed to vote,

134
00:09:44.417 --> 00:09:45.793  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
weren't allowed to go to school,

135
00:09:45.877 --> 00:09:48.755  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
you were bearing a burden
that was injurious.

136
00:09:52.341 --> 00:09:54.719  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Alexander] <i>Civil rights activists</i>
<i>began to see the necessity</i>

137
00:09:54.802 --> 00:09:57.179  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
of building not just
a civil rights movement,

138
00:09:57.263 --> 00:09:58.640  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
but a human rights movement.

139
00:09:58.723 --> 00:10:01.601  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
[Martin Luther King Jr.]
<i>And I think we should start now preparing</i>

140
00:10:01.684 --> 00:10:02.977  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>for the inevitable.</i>

141
00:10:03.060 --> 00:10:04.145  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[crowd] <i>Yeah!</i>

142
00:10:04.228 --> 00:10:07.607  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[King] <i>And let us,</i>
<i>when that moment comes...</i>

143
00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:12.569  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>go into the situations that we confront</i>

144
00:10:12.654 --> 00:10:18.575  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>with a great deal of dignity,</i>
<i>sanity and reasonableness.</i>

145
00:10:26.250 --> 00:10:29.128  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[KKK member] <i>They want to throw</i>
<i>white children and colored children</i>

146
00:10:29.211 --> 00:10:32.339  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>into the melting pot of integration,</i>

147
00:10:32.423 --> 00:10:35.176  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>through out of which</i>
<i>will come a conglomerated,</i>

148
00:10:35.259 --> 00:10:38.595  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
mulatto, mongrel class of people.

149
00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:41.307  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Both races will be destroyed
in such a movement.

150
00:10:41.891 --> 00:10:45.061  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[reporter 1] <i>We just got a report here</i>
<i>on this end that the students are in.</i>

151
00:10:45.978 --> 00:10:48.981  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[reporter 2] <i>Negroes were trying</i>
<i>to integrate the bathing beaches.</i>

152
00:10:49.065 --> 00:10:52.526  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>And the Florida Advisory Committee</i>
<i>to the US Civil Rights Commission</i>

153
00:10:52.609 --> 00:10:57.657  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>warned that the city was becoming</i>
<i>a racial superbomb with a short fuse.</i>

154
00:10:59.491 --> 00:11:03.245  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
[Alexander] <i>Civil rights activists</i>
<i>began to be portrayed in the media</i>

155
00:11:03.329 --> 00:11:06.666  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
and among, you know,
many politicians as criminals.

156
00:11:06.749 --> 00:11:09.669  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>People who are deliberately</i>
<i>violating the law,</i>

157
00:11:09.752 --> 00:11:12.296  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
<i>segregation laws</i>
<i>that existed in the South.</i>

158
00:11:14.799 --> 00:11:17.927  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[King] <i>For years now,</i>
<i>I have heard the word "wait."</i>

159
00:11:18.845 --> 00:11:23.975  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>It rings in the ear of every Negro</i>
<i>with piercing familiarity.</i>

160
00:11:24.058 --> 00:11:28.395  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>This wait has almost always meant never.</i>

161
00:11:29.939 --> 00:11:35.194  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>Justice too long delayed</i>
<i>is justice denied.</i>

162
00:11:36.153 --> 00:11:39.240  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
I think that one of the most brilliant
tactics of the civil rights movement

163
00:11:39.323 --> 00:11:41.993  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
was its transformation
of the notion of criminality.

164
00:11:42.702 --> 00:11:45.746  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
Because for the first time,
being arrested was a noble thing.

165
00:11:47.623 --> 00:11:51.210  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
Being arrested by white people
was your worst nightmare.

166
00:11:51.293 --> 00:11:54.088  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Still is, uh, for many African Americans.

167
00:11:54.171 --> 00:11:55.172  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
So what'd they do?

168
00:11:55.256 --> 00:11:59.051  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
They voluntarily defined a movement
around getting arrested.

169
00:11:59.135 --> 00:12:00.427  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
They turned it on its head.

170
00:12:04.431 --> 00:12:06.100  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[Cobb] <i>If you looked at the history</i>

171
00:12:06.183 --> 00:12:09.103  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>of black people's</i>
<i>various struggles in this country,</i>

172
00:12:09.186 --> 00:12:13.565  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
the connecting theme
is the attempt to be understood

173
00:12:13.649 --> 00:12:15.818  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>as full, complicated human beings.</i>

174
00:12:18.445 --> 00:12:22.533  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
We are something other than
this, uh, visceral image of criminality

175
00:12:22.616 --> 00:12:26.162  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>and menace and threat</i>
<i>to which people associate with us.</i>

176
00:12:26.245 --> 00:12:27.914  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[barking]

177
00:12:29.581 --> 00:12:31.542  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[protestors screaming]

178
00:12:36.047 --> 00:12:41.177  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
We're willing to be beaten for democracy,
and you misuse democracy in the street.

179
00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:44.596  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Let us lay aside irrelevant differences...

180
00:12:45.932 --> 00:12:47.558  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
and make our nation whole.

181
00:12:47.641 --> 00:12:49.143  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[applauding]

182
00:12:51.353 --> 00:12:53.772  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Gates] <i>The Civil Rights Act</i>
<i>and the Voting Rights Act said,</i>

183
00:12:53.856 --> 00:12:55.566  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>"Finally, we admit it.</i>

184
00:12:55.649 --> 00:12:58.152  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Though slavery ended in December 1865...

185
00:12:59.111 --> 00:13:03.115  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
we took away these people's rights,
and now we're gonna fix it."

186
00:13:05.284 --> 00:13:06.660  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[Marc Mauer] <i>For the first time,</i>

187
00:13:06.743 --> 00:13:10.957  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
you know, promise of equal justice
becomes at least a possibility.

188
00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:14.793  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
Their cause must be our cause, too.

189
00:13:14.877 --> 00:13:16.753  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Alexander] <i>Unfortunately,</i>
<i>at the very same time</i>

190
00:13:16.838 --> 00:13:21.217  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
that the civil rights movement
was gaining steam,

191
00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:24.178  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
crime rates were beginning to rise
in this country.

192
00:13:24.261 --> 00:13:27.723  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
Crime was increasing
in the baby boom generation

193
00:13:27.806 --> 00:13:30.684  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
that had emerged
immediately after World War II.

194
00:13:30.767 --> 00:13:31.768  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
Now they were adults.

195
00:13:31.853 --> 00:13:37.733  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
So, just through sheer demographic change,
we had an increase in the amount of crime.

196
00:13:37.816 --> 00:13:41.362  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
...and became very easy
for politicians then to say,

197
00:13:41.445 --> 00:13:47.910  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
um, that the civil rights movement itself
was contributing to rising crime rates,

198
00:13:47.994 --> 00:13:51.663  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
and that if we were to give
the Negroes their freedom, um,

199
00:13:51.747 --> 00:13:55.459  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
then we would be repaid,
as a nation, with crime.

200
00:13:57.294 --> 00:14:00.297  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Stevenson] <i>The prison population</i>
<i>in the United States was largely flat</i>

201
00:14:00.381 --> 00:14:02.091  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>throughout most of the 20th century.</i>

202
00:14:02.174 --> 00:14:04.510  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>It didn't go up a lot.</i>
<i>It didn't come down a lot.</i>

203
00:14:04.593 --> 00:14:07.221  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>But that changed in the 1970s.</i>

204
00:14:07.304 --> 00:14:09.681  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
And in the 1970s, we began an era

205
00:14:09.765 --> 00:14:13.895  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
which has been defined by this term,
"mass incarceration."

206
00:14:13.978 --> 00:14:18.065  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
This is a nation of laws,
and as Abraham Lincoln has said,

207
00:14:18.149 --> 00:14:21.527  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
"No one is above the law.
No one is below the law."

208
00:14:21.610 --> 00:14:23.445  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
And we're going to enforce the law

209
00:14:23.529 --> 00:14:27.241  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
and Americans should remember that,
if we're going to have law and order.

210
00:14:28.284 --> 00:14:32.413  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>♪ Breaking rocks out here</i>
<i>On the chain gang ♪</i>

211
00:14:32.496 --> 00:14:36.333  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>♪ Breaking rocks and serving my time ♪</i>

212
00:14:36.417 --> 00:14:40.129  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>♪ Breaking rocks out here</i>
<i>On the chain gang ♪</i>

213
00:14:40.212 --> 00:14:44.716  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>♪ Because I've been convicted of crime ♪</i>

214
00:14:44.800 --> 00:14:48.137  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>♪ Hold it steady right there</i>
<i>While I hit it ♪</i>

215
00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:53.392  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Richard Nixon] <i>Each moment in history</i>
<i>is a fleeting time, precious and unique.</i>

216
00:14:53.475 --> 00:14:56.520  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>But some stand out</i>
<i>as moments of beginning...</i>

217
00:14:57.479 --> 00:15:03.527  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>in which courses are set</i>
<i>that shape decades or centuries.</i>

218
00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:06.113  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>This can be such a moment.</i>

219
00:15:07.698 --> 00:15:12.828  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
It's with the Nixon era,
and the law and order period

220
00:15:12.912 --> 00:15:16.415  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
when crime begins to stand in for race.

221
00:15:16.498 --> 00:15:19.668  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
If there is one area
where the word "war" is appropriate,

222
00:15:19.751 --> 00:15:21.837  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
it is in the fight against crime.

223
00:15:21.921 --> 00:15:24.340  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Part of what he talked about
was a war on crime.

224
00:15:24.423 --> 00:15:26.968  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
But that was one of those code words,

225
00:15:27.051 --> 00:15:29.470  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
what we might call
"dog-whistle politics" now,

226
00:15:29.553 --> 00:15:31.222  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:10.00% 
which really was referring to

227
00:15:31.305 --> 00:15:34.600  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
the black political movements of the day,
Black Power, Black Panthers,

228
00:15:34.683 --> 00:15:35.935  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>the antiwar movement,</i>

229
00:15:36.018 --> 00:15:38.562  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>the movements for women's</i>
<i>and gay liberation at that time,</i>

230
00:15:38.645 --> 00:15:41.607  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
which Nixon felt compelled
to fight back against.

231
00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:45.902  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Once the federal government,
through the FBI, moves into an area,

232
00:15:45.987 --> 00:15:48.739  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
this should be warning
to those who engage in these acts

233
00:15:48.822 --> 00:15:52.493  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>that they eventually</i>
<i>are going to be apprehended.</i>

234
00:15:52.576 --> 00:15:55.162  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Cobb] <i>There's this outcry</i>
<i>for law and order.</i>

235
00:15:55.997 --> 00:15:59.333  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
And Nixon becomes the person
who articulates that perfectly.

236
00:15:59.416 --> 00:16:03.254  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Nixon] <i>There can be no progress</i>
<i>in America without respect for law.</i>

237
00:16:03.337 --> 00:16:06.298  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
Many people felt like, uh,
we were losing control.

238
00:16:07.967 --> 00:16:11.595  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
[Nixon] <i>We need total war</i>
<i>in the United States</i>

239
00:16:11.678 --> 00:16:15.432  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
against the evils, uh,
that we see in our cities.

240
00:16:17.143 --> 00:16:20.896  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>Federal spending</i>
<i>for local law enforcement will double.</i>

241
00:16:20.980 --> 00:16:22.439  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>Time is running out</i>
<i>for the merchants</i>

242
00:16:22.523 --> 00:16:25.151  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
<i>of crime and corruption</i>
<i>in American society.</i>

243
00:16:25.234 --> 00:16:26.235  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
[siren wailing]

244
00:16:26.318 --> 00:16:29.696  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
The wave of crime is not going to be
the wave of the future

245
00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:32.074  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
<i>in the United States of America.</i>

246
00:16:32.158 --> 00:16:34.994  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
We must wage
what I have called "total war"

247
00:16:35.077 --> 00:16:38.539  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
against public enemy number one
in the United States,

248
00:16:38.622 --> 00:16:39.956  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
the problem of dangerous drugs.

249
00:16:40.041 --> 00:16:41.625  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
"A war on drugs."

250
00:16:41.708 --> 00:16:46.172  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:84.67% 
And that utterance gave birth to this era,

251
00:16:46.255 --> 00:16:49.716  position:50.00%,middle  align:middle size:80.00%  line:79.33% 
where we decided to deal
